Gaussian Naive Bayes
Definition
Gaussian Naive Bayes is used when the input features are continuous numerical values that follow a normal (Gaussian) distribution. It assumes that each feature is normally distributed within every class. This algorithm is widely used for datasets containing measurements such as height, weight, age, or temperature.
Flowchart

              Gaussian Naive Bayes
                       │
                       ▼
             Input Continuous Data
                       │
                       ▼
        Assume Normal Distribution
                       │
                       ▼
      Calculate Mean and Variance
                       │
                       ▼
        Apply Bayes' Theorem
                       │
                       ▼
          Final Class Prediction
Examples
	• Disease Diagnosis 
	• Weather Prediction 
	• Blood Pressure Classification 
	• Student Performance Prediction 

3.2 Multinomial Naive Bayes
Definition
Multinomial Naive Bayes is used when the features represent frequency or count data. It is commonly applied in text classification, where the number of times a word appears in a document is important. The algorithm estimates the probability of a document belonging to a class based on word frequencies.
Flowchart

            Multinomial Naive Bayes
                     │
                     ▼
              Input Count Data
                     │
                     ▼
         Count Frequency of Features
                     │
                     ▼
          Apply Bayes' Theorem
                     │
                     ▼
          Final Class Prediction
Examples
	• Email Spam Detection 
	• News Article Classification 
	• Language Identification 
	• Document Categorization 

3.3 Bernoulli Naive Bayes
Definition
Bernoulli Naive Bayes is used when the input features are binary, meaning they can take only two possible values such as 0 or 1, Yes or No, or True or False. It focuses on whether a feature is present or absent rather than how many times it appears.
Flowchart

            Bernoulli Naive Bayes
                     │
                     ▼
            Input Binary Features
                     │
                     ▼
       Check Presence or Absence
                     │
                     ▼
          Apply Bayes' Theorem
                     │
                     ▼
          Final Class Prediction
Examples
	• Spam Detection (Word Present/Not Present) 
	• Product Recommendation 
	• Disease Detection (Symptom Present/Absent) 
	• Fraud Detection 

3.4 Complement Naive Bayes
Definition
Complement Naive Bayes is an improved version of Multinomial Naive Bayes designed to handle imbalanced datasets, where one class has significantly more samples than another. It calculates probabilities using the complement of each class, which often improves classification accuracy for minority classes.
