                      │
                      ▼
          Final Class Prediction
Examples
	• Fraud Detection 
	• Medical Diagnosis 
	• Rare Disease Prediction 
	• Customer Churn Prediction 

4. Working of Naive Bayes
Step 1: Collect the Dataset
Prepare the labelled training data.
Example:
Email	Class
"Win Prize"	Spam
"Meeting Today"	Not Spam
"Free Offer"	Spam

Step 2: Calculate Prior Probability
Determine how often each class occurs.
Example:
Spam = 2/3
Not Spam = 1/3

Step 3: Calculate Likelihood
Compute the probability of each feature occurring in each class.
Example:
P("Free"|Spam)

Step 4: Apply Bayes' Theorem
Calculate the posterior probability for each class.

Step 5: Select the Highest Probability
The class with the highest probability is chosen as the final prediction.

Example
Suppose an email contains the words:
"Free Prize"
The algorithm calculates:
Probability of Spam = 0.92
Probability of Not Spam = 0.08
Since 0.92 > 0.08
Prediction = Spam

Advantages
	• Simple and easy to implement. 
	• Fast training and prediction. 
	• Works well with high-dimensional data. 
	• Effective for text classification tasks. 
	• Requires less training data. 
	• Handles multiclass classification naturally. 

Disadvantages
	• Assumes features are independent, which is not always true. 
	• Performance decreases when features are highly correlated. 
	• Zero-frequency problems may occur if smoothing is not used. 
	• Less accurate than some advanced algorithms on complex datasets. 

